Mamoru Shinozaki was a high-ranking Japanese official who put himself at risk by secretly saving thousands of people from the Sook Ching operation in 1942. 
His nickname, the "Schindler of Singapore", was given to him because of the similarities his story bore to German hero Oskar Schindler.
